			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1844">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>People regularly write to complain that <em>The Sun</em> is too dark and dreary, but lately it&rsquo;s been entirely too funny. The irate reactions to Sparrow&rsquo;s poems and essays really got me cheering. It took a lot of gall for you to publish his &ldquo;<a href="/article/455">Brief History of My Money-Back Guarantee</a>&rdquo; [May 2004] &mdash; the closing chapter on one of the funniest sequences I&rsquo;ve seen in print.</p>

<p>What&rsquo;s up with all this humor? You have really crossed the line. Tom Ireland&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/464">The Woman in Question</a>&rdquo; [April 2004] was full of gentle, wry humor, and uplifting to boot. I actually snorted out loud while reading Dwight Yates&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/461">Our Impending Reconciliation</a>&rdquo; [May 2004] on the airplane. Other passengers took notice. Boy, did that piss me off!</p>

<p><em>The Sun</em> had better get back to its bleak, dreary old self or get ready for some subscription cancellations. You have no right to make people laugh.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jeff Droubay<br>Upland, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1845">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>On issues discussed in your <a href="/issues/339/correspondence">March 2004 Correspondence</a>:</p>

<p>Sparrow is right about the fictional character Tonto being dehumanized. &ldquo;Tonto&rdquo; is Spanish for &ldquo;stupid,&rdquo; and the Lone Ranger is merely a romanticized notion popularized by fifties television. Here in Phoenix, we recently struggled with another dehumanizing name, &ldquo;squaw,&rdquo; which translates to &ldquo;cunt&rdquo; in the Hopi language. Though our governor succeeded in changing the name of Squaw Peak to Piestewa Peak &mdash; to honor Private First Class Lori Piestewa, who was killed in the Iraq war &mdash; the public resistance to the change was shameful. We Americans seem unwilling to educate ourselves beyond the point of being just smart enough to be dangerous.</p>

<p>To the reader who wrote that George W. Bush&rsquo;s goal in our war with Iraq is to bring &ldquo;peace and economic expansion for America and the rest of the world,&rdquo; I say: &ldquo;Fighting for peace is like screwing for virginity.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Marsha Gilliam<br>Phoenix, Arizona</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

